<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><refentry version="5.0-subset Scilab" xml:id="bwboundaries" xml:lang="en" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><refnamediv><refname>bwboundaries</refname><refpurpose>Extract contours from a binary image.</refpurpose></refnamediv><refsynopsisdiv><title>Syntax</title><synopsis>boundaries = bwboundaries(image); boundaries = bwboundaries(image, rmode, method)</synopsis></refsynopsisdiv><refsection><title>Parameters</title><variablelist><varlistentry><term>image</term><listitem><para>Binary or numeric 2D image.</para></listitem></varlistentry><varlistentry><term>rmode</term><listitem><para>OpenCV contour retrieval mode. Default is 2.</para></listitem></varlistentry><varlistentry><term>method</term><listitem><para>OpenCV contour approximation method. Default is 1.</para></listitem></varlistentry><varlistentry><term>boundaries</term><listitem><para>Scilab list of contour point matrices.</para></listitem></varlistentry></variablelist></refsection><refsection><title>Description</title><para><function>bwboundaries</function> is a MATLAB-style contour entry point backed by <function>imfindContours</function>. It returns IPCV contour lists rather than MATLAB cell arrays.</para></refsection><refsection><title>Examples</title><programlisting><![CDATA[image = imread(fullpath(getIPCVpath() + "/images/coins_gray.jpg")); boundaries = bwboundaries(imbinarize(image));]]></programlisting></refsection><refsection role="see also"><title>See also</title><simplelist type="inline"><member><link linkend="imfindContours">imfindContours</link></member><member><link linkend="imcontourarea">imcontourarea</link></member></simplelist></refsection><refsection><title>Authors</title><simplelist type="vert"><member>Tan Chin Luh</member></simplelist></refsection><refsection><title>History</title><informaltable border="1"><tr><td>Version</td><td>Description</td></tr><tr><td>5.0.0</td><td>Compatibility entry point introduced in development Step 3.</td></tr></informaltable></refsection></refentry>
